  "texts": [
    "Later work (Schneider et al. 2020) illustrates how focusing on one type of robustness may provide limited insight into other types:",
    "1 3 \"We here argue that popular benchmarks to measure model robustness against common corruptions (like ImageNet-C) underestimate model robustness in many (but not all) application scenarios.\"",
    "\"So far, popular image corruption benchmarks like ImageNet-C focus only on ad hoc scenarios in which the tested model has zero prior knowledge about the corruptions it encounters during test time, even if it encounters the same corruption multiple times.\"",
    "6.5.3 Net benefit, calibration, threshold selection, and training objectives for algorithmic fairness in healthcare (Pfohl et al. 2022a) This work compares the estimated net utility of predictive systems in healthcare.",
    "Specifically, the authors train predictive systems that output a continuous-valued risk score (risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease), which serves as the sole basis for a hypothetical clinical intervention (statin initiation based on decision thresholds)."
  ]
}